text: UPDATED: APR 4, 2017 From the tap at Italian restraunt in Milwaukee. The aroma is caramel and orange, Apearance is amber in color. Its medium sweet with a light bitterness. Finishes with caramel, nuts, and orange

rich gold with some red. fast dissipating foam. Aroma rich creamy caramel. cow tails candy. tastes big buttery caramel, grain. super clean. full bodied yet comes up slightly crisp. not getting cascade really, seems spicy/noble hops. good.
Bottle. Amber in color with an off-white head. Light malty with caramel flavor. Semi sweet finish.
B-. Pours a murky amber color with white head. Caramel and toasty aroma & flavors.

0.33l bottle. Pours amber colour with medium size off white head, clear liquid. Aroma of fresh baked bread, corn syrup. Medium sweet, very low bitterness. Medium body, oily feel, very gentle caramel aftetaste
On tap at B Dubs. Amber pour with an off-white head. Taste and aroma of caramel malt and hops, Nice enough.
Not a big fan, tastes kinda generic for some reason, not bad dont get me wrong.

I got to enjoy Riverwest Stein with some fried cheese curds and some golden-brown strips of fried lake perch. Its hard to get more Wisconsin than that. Hard to dream up a better pairing for the meal, too. Riverwest Stein pours amber and has a decidedly malt-forward aroma. Flavor is lightly toasty and has lots of caramel sweetness. For all the maltiness, theres a quick, smooth finish with just a flash of hops. Not the most complex beer out there, but its undeniably tasty.

Intense grain and bread malts, caramel. Clear, dark gold, medium, creamy, off-white head. Medium sweet. More sweet grain malts, lively carbonation, light bitterness coming up in the finish. OK Amber, nothing too spectacular though. Keg at brewery, Milwaukee.
On tap in Burlington Iowa afternoon before the Dead & Co show. Pretty disappointing. Some malt and bread flavors, but generally a cardboardy lager quality.

Aroma: malt, bread
Taste: malt, bread and nuts from the start. Sweet caramel in the background. Well balanced by grass hops. One of the best in its style
From bottle. Pours clear amber with medium off white head. Aroma of malts, bread, caramel. Medium, creamy body with soft carbonation. Taste is medium to light sweet, light bitter. Good.

Drank this beer from a glass poured from a bottle, 
this beer had a medium to dark brown and red pour with a good mix of haze and gave a one finger white and faint off-white cover that receded to a ring and thin layer of bubbles, it left some small fingers and spots of lacing on the glass, 

the nose had munich malt with some melanoidins, a little dark toasted malt, some toasted bread and caramel like notes with light hops, a little malt sweetness, 

there was munich malt with dark malt flavors, light citrus and spice hops, some dark toasted bread and faint caramel with malt/bread medium sweetness, there was a hint of brown sugar like sweetness but not quite there, 

the mouth feel was light with average carbonation, it was creamy on the lips, 

this beer resembled a dark amber beer with a mix of dark Octoberfest beer on the nose and flavor, it was tasty and in some ways reminds me of the Shorts older version of Noble Chaos before they changed the beer to its current state, this was a good drink.
Thank you, Lakefront Brewery, there in Milwaukee; this, too, is a beer that should make Milwaukee famous.

Aroma - toasted malt and spiced hops.
Appearance - the body is hazy, unfiltered, and amber in color. The head is about 1" and off-white. Head sticks around for a while, and fades into a small slice.
Taste - caramel malt, with some spiced hops. There is a slight oak about the flavor.
Palate - medium body, slight creaminess, average carbonation, and a slight pungent bitter finish.

Bottle from variety case. Pours an amber color with a generous head. Staying power too. Aroma is timid with fresh caramel malts. Creamy palate. Smooth beer. Slight hops. Tofee biscuit notes. Medium light body. I enjoyed this beer. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
This beer is a sweet treat. If you like desserts. Im diabetic. I want to like the flavor she gives me, but its an insulin depleting challenge.

Pours a hazy amber-orange with many fine particles and a decent khaki-cream head that leaves some soapy, stringy lace. Nose involves toasted malt, lightly metallic lager yeast, some noble hop spice and light pine. Pretty sweet, fairly bitter. Medium bodied, oily, active, with a toasty lager finish. Nice amber lager.
12 oz bottle from the sampler case. This is an above average amber lager but it still reminds me of drinking something artificial in its redness. Dont let that dissuade you from trying it yourself.

12 oz bottle from J J Liquors in Edgewater. Clear amber appearance with red hues and a beige head. Clean, malty, smooth and rich with notes of toasted grain, light caramel, toffee and bread. Solid, easy drinking amber lager overall.
This one is light biscuit up front, a candy sweet middle, and a barnyard aftertaste.
Clear amber lager. Roasty and sweet Aroma and taste. Well balanced and malty, the hops do help cut through some of the malt. Refreshing and crisp like a lager. Slightly spicy

12 ounce bottle into lager glass, best before 11/19/2015. Pours slightly hazy reddish copper color with a 1 finger dense off white head with great retention, that reduces to a nice cap that lingers. Nice spotty soapy lacing clings down the glass, with a good amount of streaming carbonation retaining the head. Aromas of caramel, toast, biscuit, light nuttiness, light lemon/orange zest, herbal, grass, light pepper, and yeast earthiness. Very nice aromas with good balance of dark/bready malt and citrus/earthy hop notes; with good strength. Taste of caramel, toast, biscuit, light nuttiness, light lemon/orange zest, herbal, grass, light pepper, and yeast earthiness. Light earthy/spicy bitterness on the finish; with lingering notes of caramel, toast, biscuit, light nuttiness, herbal, grass, light pepper, and yeast earthiness on the finish for a short bit. Light-moderate dryness after the finish. Very nice robustness and balance of dark/bready malt and citrus/earthy hop flavors; with a good malt/bitterness balance and zero cloying flavors after the finish. Very clean on lager flavors with minimal yeast ester notes present. Medium carbonation and body; with a very smooth and fairly creamy/bready mouthfeel that is nice. Alcohol is very well hidden with minimal warming present after the finish. Overall this is a very nice Vienna lager style. All around good robustness and balance of dark/bready malt and citrus/earthy hop flavors; and very smooth and easy to drink. A very enjoyable offering.

Was hoping I stumbled on a true Stein beer but alas, just a play on words....such is life....pours a cream soda brown color with a pillowy head which lingers.....aroma of very little, slight malt sweetness....taste is hay, sweet grass stalks, tails off into slight metallic finish. Not crazy about this one.

Went to a great steak house with no good beer. I had to settle for this. Not my style of beer. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Nice amber that has a bit of alcohol. Unlike the fixed beer this one doesn't have red malts, just amber.

Bottle - Has an almost weird poop brown cloudy color to it with a constant stream of bubbles and no head. The smell reminds me of my grandfathers dairy farm, no only hay and malt but the barn comes to mind too. As for the taste, rather plain and boring. Lots of malt on the palate and no hops. For my tastes not a good choice, lacks character and depth.

IMHO there is a big difference between amber ales and amber lagers, and I much prefer the latter. Riverwest Stein is a great example. Amber in color, malty and mouthy, but refreshing at the same time. Ales with a similar maltiness tend to be too sweet and less refreshing... must be something about the lagering.

Aroma caramel, 
Appearance amber, hazy, tan foam, 
Taste medium sweetness, lightly bitter, 
Palate light body, thin feel, flat, 
Overall I would not suggest this beer to anyone
36cl, as Riverwest Stein Beer, no mention of ABV, American brew, from De Hopduvel Gent, not complex brew, malty/sweet and slightly floral/woody, balanced, hazy, small head, nice brew

Draft. Clear Amber color with tan head; substantial lacing. Malty aroma. Toasted malt upfront with a finish with biscuit balanced by bitterness. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Poured a translucent amber with a 5mm of off-white foam head that diminished quickly to a collar that laced poorly. Carbonation very high and fine. Aroma subtly of sweet caramel malt. Taste bland with some sweet caramel and a hint of hops bitterness. Light body, a bit thin. Light, smooth, sweetness, a hint of bitterness but fairly bland.

"i was intrigued by the premise of this all malt amber lager, but it was another miss. slight fart character to the aroma (nice, no?). the flavor was unique, but not good enough to make up for the otherwise unimpressive beer."

[ Keg ][ 5oz ][ Lakefront ][ $1.50 ][ Plastic Cup ][ 8.18.14 ]
>> Clear deep orange pour, weak head. Nose is super sweet malt. Sugary taste, grenadine and sweet cherries, sticky, cloying, all sugar. Nope.

Poured from 12 oz bottle into pint glass.

Appearance: pours a thin off white head that recedes leaving some light lacing. Color is a rich, cloudy amber with abundant streaming carbonation.

Aroma: sweet caramel, bread dough, a hint of pine and citrus

Mouthfeel: light to medium bodied, frothy, with a quite dry finish.

Flavor: caramel, butterscotch, raisins, toasted bread, with some herbal and citrus rind hops in the finish.

Overall: very well done and enjoyable. Should pair well with many foods.
dark amber color; caramel malt aroma; a medium bodied beer with a toasty, slightly sweet, caramel malt flavor

On tap, poured into a sampler glass. The aroma is toast, caramel, juicy orange, and a touch of nuts. It pours a bright, clear amber color with a soft and creamy white head that retains a thick ring with a spattering of head skimming the surface. It leaves an ok lace. Its a medium sweet with a light bitterness. The texture is oily with a medium body and a good amount of soft carbonation. It finishes with caramel, nuts, and orange blossoms and leaves a mild, malty, toasted bread aftertaste.
Carmely and malty. Big flavor. Red with white head. Bread and earthy. Had this on draft at lakefront brewery taproom

香りが弱い  
味も弱め
甘さ  
飲みやすいけ&

On tap at our hotel in Milwaukee.

The beer is dark copper with a mild haze and sports a half inch off off-white head. The aroma bring caramel malt, bread, grain, a hint of sweetness and mild alcohol. Perhaps a touch of citrus in the flavor with a light bitterness in the finish. Pretty drinkable, though the beer itself is rather bland and uneventful. Ok...

Thanks to Henshawb for this. Poured a clear copper color with almost no head that disappeared instantly. Nose has a slightly roasted maltiness and really not much else. Tastes fairly bland but this is the reason i dont drink too many lagers. Slight caramel but mostly a bland maltiness that leaves my realizing why i dont buy american lagers for the most part.

355ml bottle from Archive Beer Boutique 170513. Big bold amber colour with a cracking head that settles to an even layer of foam. Clear in the glass with caramel, biscuit and malt aromas. Full bodied with a creamy smooth mouthfeel.
Biscuity malt caramel nose and taste. Low carbonation minimal hops. Slightly spicy. Not the strongest tasting, a good session ale. Quite nice!
Aroma is deep roasty malts with deep caramel character. Taste is sweet malts and rich roasty taste. Body is a cloudy brown with a thin lace head that retains poorly.
A very good amber lager. Roasted malt and barley on the nose with just a hint of pine. Finishes with a sweet caramel note. A small amount of floral hop flavor does sneak in on the palate.
ince and not so amber. More like a Red ale but refreshing. Not too bitter neither malty. Nice to drink.

Bottle from Ashur Liquor in variety 8 pack: Poured a simple golden honey color with a thin layer of weak foaming head. As for the aroma, there is a scent of cheap perfume and corn replacement for malt. The flavor is bland and the only flavor I pick up on is a taste of medicine or of some kind of cheap cough syrup. Another disappointing beer by this brewing company.

Poured from bottle into tulip glass, good looking amber color with a good sized head. Really like the taste of this lager, nice caramel toasty flavor with just a hint of bitterness making for a great finish. Very drinkable beer, would definitely have another.

12 oz bottle pours amber with a off white head. Aroma of caramel malts, grain and grass. Taste is malts, nutty and grain.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Beautiful amber color, nice caramel and maltiness flavor with good hop balance. Great traditional German beer.
This is a very tasted amber lager. Nice deep amber color and rich foamy head. This is a very enjoyable beer. Enjoy!

Slowbeer bottle (27-Dec-2013) Light fruit and toffee malt aroma. Brown amber colour, poor head and suds lacing. Simple fruit berry and light roast malt flavour. Medium bitter fruit hop finish and light toffee malt aftertaste.

Malt hop honey aroma. Deer amber colour poor head and lacing. Malt herbal honey flavour. Flat palate.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

A - pours clear glowing amber with 1 finger head. Some sticky lacing. S - such light aromas. Floral, lightly nutty, quiet dark malts. M - light medium easy drinking body. Light bitter end. T - simple nutty, darker malts, some bitter citrusy hops. O - simple amber. 3.1
A good beer. Not the greatest one Ive had, but Id drink it again. It is Fixed Gear. American Red Ale

DATE TASTED: November 16, 2013... GLASSWARE: Sam Adams lager glass... OCCASION: TWO rates in one night--feeling good!... APPEARANCE: solid orange amber body; pours a Santas beard-white head, frothy and thick; lacing is sporadic but significant... AROMA: malty and confidently so...pleasant hint of caramel, candied sugars and faint hints of floral hops... PALATE: somewhat smooth; simply a slick, aptly medium-bodied presence with a lingering aftertaste...TASTE: indeed malty; borderline dunkel/doppelbock base; flat, singular effect...OVERALL: caught off-guard by the five-finger malt punch this brew delivers; liking the eight-beer mix pack Lakefront puts out more and more; not a standout but one that pairs well with rainy November nights like this...
Bottle. Pours caramel brown with white head. Nose and taste of toasted malt, toasted grain, toasted barley, light smoke and pine wood. Medium body.
12oz bottle. Amber in color with a decent off-white head. Aroma is of sweet malts, caramel with light bread dough. Taste is of caramel, sweet malts, sweet bread, and light woody hops.

Bottle shared at a tasting at Dancing Camel. Pours orange to red with a nice fluffy head, aroma of honey, some roasted notes, some yeasty tones, malt complexity, caramelish tones, flavor of malt, honey, werthers, toffee, slightly bitter, medium bodied

10/10/13 the LAST bottle of the 8 pack bought for the Poconos 2 weeks ago and my favorite out of the pack. Dark amber color with a very thin head. Aroma is lots of malt and caramel. Flavor is a little sweet almost octoberfest like. Good beer

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

12 oz bottle. (Lakefront Brewery) Milwaukee, WI.
Clear copper colour with a small off-white head. 
Mild sweet toffee, malt and banana in the aroma. 
The flavour is quite easy but theres nothing wrong with it. Dryish malt, banana sweetness and mild hoppy bitterness. I dont know what the banana is doing here. Drinkable, forgettable.

UPDATED: MAR 30, 2015 12 oz bottle Another beer tasted at a Packer game tailgate. The lager poured a deep copper color with a beige head. The aroma was of caramel malts. This lager had a rich taste of caramel and peach. The medium body lager had average carbonation. This was one of the best beers tasted at the tailgate. The finish was smooth with no bitterness.

Bottle sample at a tasting at Dancing Camel. Thanks zvikar. Clear amber. Weak aroma with malt, a bit of caramel, some oxidation and something weird. Sweetish flavor with a bit of malt and caramel, honey-ish oxidation notes and a drier finish with faint bitterness. Rather light-bodied.

Better than expected, stein-by-name only Vienna lager with full and round fruity malts qualities, grain character, a smooth, "fat" yet clean palate and just enough earthy-floral hops to balance those out.

After wiping away the tears of upset from my cheeks at the realisation this is in fact not a steinbier it was on to the tasting. Nutty, sherryish and earthy nose with plenty of punch from what seems like swarf-bin rust and boiled kelp. A good lot of citrus and fell stone fruit in there too - a little too leftfield for a Vienna. Settles a cloudy tawny orange with a mist of floaties. Headless. A mild burnt twig note edges a lot of rich, sweet and biscuity malt on the palate. Peppery backend with a similarly spicy, woody and herbal finish. A little citrus breaks it up. Very lean in body with sprightly effervescence. Sweetens further as it warms so chilled is the only drinking option. Rough around the edges yet drinkable. Just doesnt pull it off though!! (12fl.Oz, BBE 03/14, The Freo Doctor Liquor Store, Fremantle)

12oz bottle. Pours a clear amber/copper color with a finger of off white head. Aroma of roasted and caramel malts, grass, and light citrus hops. Taste is identical. Roasted and caramel malts up front, followed by some grassiness, and some citrus bitterness in the finish. 

T - The hops are subtle in the nose but really show up in the flavor. The toasted caramel is bold without the sweetness. Bready with a hint of nutmeg. Citrus hops are a welcomed tartness. The finish is crisp and slightly grassy.
A dark amber color with a head that lasts well after the initial pour. A very malty taste, yet a relatively clean finish.
Bottled. Pouts a clear amber red. Light head. Aroma is light malts. caramel bread and hint of fruits. Good.
Tart and hoppy aroma. Dark golden amber color. Cream tan head. Tastes malty with a bit of fruit finish.

Clear amber color. Low carbonation. Aroma is of American hops. Very thin body and flavor. Aftertaste is of west coast hops. This tastes like they used a cheap malt base and then tried to doctor it up with specialty malts and lots of oily hops. "Stein Beer"? Well if a gimmick is all you got .............
Draft. Pours a dark amber with a half finger of white head. Aroma of caramel and pale malt. Taste is about the same. Light caramel and toffee. Very enjoyable but nothing too special.
A clear amber color, Scents of malt and light yeast. The full flavor of the malts hit you first but the crispness of the lager still come though. Palate fades quickly leaving a light malt coating.
Draft at the brewery. The color of an aged, bronze statue. Drinks with a light, sweet malt, like a little bit of light caramel candy. Middle of the road offering. (#5142, 7/5/2013)
355 mLbottle. Pours clear amber with a light lager yeast aroma, fresh lemon zest with a herb like hint. Similar flavour, I dont get much Carmel/toffee at all. This beer isnt my cup of tea.
Bottle. Medium amber with a light golden head. Aroma is lightly toasty caramel. Flavour is the same, with a metallic bitterness in the finish that I didnt dig.
user_location: the land of bitumen, beef & beer, Alberta, CANADA

text: Pours orange and settles into a caramel color. Aroma is feint. Malty hoppy taste, but not excessively bitter.
A very nice bready beer. Mild and drinkable. Grass and caramel flavors. A little citrusy aroma.

Great malty beer. Not heavy, but lots of flavor. Beautiful amber color with nice aroma.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Hazy amber pour with minimal tan head. Aroma of malt and caramel with a bit of toasted notes. Taste is mainly sweet but there is a bit of bitter crisp to the finish. Overall a decent beer

caramel, bread, floral, dough, amber, hazy, tan foam, medium sweetness, lightly bitter, lightly sour, medium body, creamy, average carbonation, 
My first rating ever as a maturing beer drinker,  not real heavy and bitter but had enough flavors to be very good drinking.
Solid malt forward amber ale.  Nothing special but probably one of lakefronts better beers.
Hazy dark amber. Medium to small creamy off-white head; lasting. Malty and sweet. Caramel. smooth and well put-together. Very drinkable. A go-to beer at Milwaukee street festivals.
Bottle. Amber color with a nice big, slightly whitish tan head. Taste is malty, caramel but not too sweet. Aroma is caramel and a little candy corn.

Bottle. Amber with an off-white head. Aroma is of toasted caramel, a little floral too. Malty and clean with balancing bitterness, some spices at the end. Solid beer with fine balance, albeit not all that tasty for its strength.

Had on draft at the Revere Tavern in Delafield, WI. Came in a traditional 16oz  Irish glass. Amber shade with a small white head. This is a great beer for malt lovers. Has a nice crisp finish. Overall very enjoyable. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
Nice amber/copper color; Medium slightly creamy body; Aroma of toasted malt, hops, & caramel; Flavor of malt, caramel, hops, and light citrus; Crisp finish; Nicely balanced; Solid lager.
More OK than good, has a number of nice elements but nothing that really stands out. Definitely a good choice to drink if presented, but wouldnt go out of my way to find.
Tap @ a Brewers game - good size foamy head, nice dark amber color, caramel malt aroma and flavor with a good hop balance, very drinkable, perfect for the game

Pours a clear amber colour with a small white spotty head head. Aroma is caramel malt, toasted malts, overall a clean malty aroma. Flavour is sweet, toasted malts, a nice soft malt profile, mild bitterness and a mildly dry finish.
Bottle from Mane Liquor. Very inoffensive stuff. Not great but not bad either. Very malt driven with a touch of sweetness behind it and some floral hops. Solid session stuff
Sample at brewfest. Really average aroma, but great taste. Lots of caramel and hops coming through, very solid.
April 11, 2013 - bottle at work event. Clear brownish orange pour with some head. Aroma and taste of malt and some hops. Some carbonation and light to medium body.
a little bit of a bitter taste at the end but overall an excellent beer. I will definately be getting this again.

Draft at filling station. Deep brown. Malty. Easy drinking. Nothing special but better then most

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone

Bottle. Looks like buckwheat honey with a lightly red fleeting head.  The aroma is moderately sweet clean caramel malt with fresh light fruity and floral notes that cuts balance the malt.  The flavor is similar with a earthy malty richness followed by a clean and lightly bitter end. The mouthfeel is simple, smooth, and quaffable. A simple well made and very drinkable beer that I would buy for any non-beer nerd gathering.

Not bad!  If you like malt, this ones for you.  I really like the copper pour with a big white head that leaves some lacing.  The aroma is malt heavy just like the taste.  Its clean and well balanced - quite drinkable.

A good vienna, the malt sweetness dominates but the hops comes through, actually maybe a tad much.  But smooth and a little creamy. A little biscuity.  palate maybe just a little syrupy.  Overall, not bad at all.
Amber with white head. Musty odor. Maybe some caramel. I can drink this, but wont.

Pours a clear amber/orange with a robust off white head.  Spicy caramel aroma.  Taste is a clean fresh sweet caramel malt, a butteriness and medium hoppiness that balances well.  Very good effort, but a bit more hop spiciness than a classic Vienna.

A - Pours an amber copper. 2 finger off-white head.

S - Roasted caramel malt. Fresh bread with some grassy grain. Some light citrus hops.

T - The hops are subtle in the nose but really show up in the flavor. The toasted caramel is bold without the sweetness. Bready with a hint of nutmeg. Citrus hops are a welcomed tartness. The finish is crisp and slightly grassy.

M - Medium body with moderate carbonation.

A very good Amber. It smells sweeter than it tastes. The hops compliment the malt beautifully. Very balanced.

Serving type: bottle

09-26-2010
On tap at the brewery. Aroma is of roasted malt. Flavor is bright slightly sweet and caramelized. A solid vienna.

Pint at soblemans in milwaukee.  Awesome color, as viennas do.  I think this may be one of the best lagers i have ever had.  Great bitter taste, not a hoppy bitter but still good.  Really good mouth feel.  Definitely would get again, probably one of lakefronts best beers.

Aroma is slightly yeasty and caramel. Pours reddish amber. Pillowy white head, that recedes to an outer ring. Flavor is a lightly roasted malt center with dry, slightly spicey (cloves, resin) finish. Medium light body. Very drinkable, nicely balanced.

Bottle - Bitter roasted malts.  Clear amber with a thin head.  Very malt forward, with enough bitterness to cut the cloying sweetness.  Bit of spice and hops in the finish.  Not my style, but I can appreciate this for what it is.

First off, let me confess I dont have great expectations of this , or any other beer with "Amber" on the label. But, that said, this isnt bad.  Clear light copper color, sweet with hints of roasty caramel and wildflowers, not much in the cascade hops but still has a touch of bitterness in the follow. I dont recall having a beer with Willamen hops, that must be the scent I cant quite nail down. Has a slight mineral quality as well.

Pours a clear amber color with a decent head that leaves some lacing. Scent is very heavy with malts as to be expected from the label on the bottle reading "All Malt." Has a really good taste to it that is very well mixed. Very malty but also has some nut hints and sweet caramel. Leaves a good after taste. A very tasty and well made Red Lager.

Pretty clear amber,some head,some lacing-sugary decending thick retention.
Kind of a unique aroma, has some fruit and malt and distinct unusual sweet  aroma. Maybe german malt/or type of yeast?
Taste is smooth,lightly slick,medium body,stronger carmel malt notes,toffee,mild fruit-not citrus but the ripeish fruit.Some breadiness.Finish has mild citrus/pepper. Somewhat impressed.Not a favorate style but havent tried this style alot either,this is pretty good.
Deep redish brown pour.  Mostly caramel malt and some lightly toasted malt.  Flavor is a thin caramel tasting brew with light toasted malt hints and light generic hop finish.  Okay, but generic.
Pours brown,  hardely any head...  very easy drinking and smooth,  some spice,  caramel light hopps..  Not bad

Cloudy brown, with a tall, light tan head.
Scent is caramel, slightly sweet..
A bit watery.
A little bitter taste in background....
Drinkable, but boring.

Orange-brown lager thats lighter than it looks. Caramel mostly, minimal hops. A bit burnt in the aftertaste, though not unpleasantly so. Iffy echoes of cheapness persist, though that may be simply memories of inferior lagers coming to the fore.
Nice sweet malty aroma.  Dark amber in color with a tan head.   Sweet malt with heavy caramel character,  Has a nice malty finish with slight hint of some hop bitterness.  Solid
Caramel pour lingering head. Slightly skunky aroma at first. Semi sweet and malty. Fairly light.
Soft bock aroma from a caramel colored beer; mild aroma in the front with a end that finishes a bit murky. Average bock. (bottle at Ale Jail beer festival, September 2012)

Pours medium amber with a medium tan head. Caramel, biscuit, and toast malt, but not overpowering. Soft carbonation, slick feel with long finish. Medium sweet, light bitterness. This is a very drinkable beer with nice malt flavor.

-Fish!
Tap at the brewery. Rating #443. Amber pour. Light toast and very malty, but a very tasty and drinkable beer. (2430)
user_location: Redlands, by way of Wisconsin,, California, USA

text: amber with small head. sweet caramel malts and slight hops. smooth and easy to drink.

Amber colored.  Sweet malt and spice aroma.  Same with the taste.  Subtle hop afterbite.  Lucky to live in Milwaukee and have this readily available at places with otherwise crappy beer choices.  Its just good.

This was really pleasing. Lagers in a general sense have lost their appeal for me as of late, so this was a nice surprise. The aroma had a malty spiciness that had me anticipating what was next. Brown cloudy color with a two-finger head of foam. I know Marzens can fall into this category but this beer did not remind me of that. The unique malt flavor almost seemed to have a clove presence. I wish I had bought more of this.
Bottle. Toasty caramel malt aroma.  Hazy amber with a small beige head, spotty lacing. Flavor is in keeping with the aroma, toasty caramel malt with a light grassy finish. Very nice.

Bottle @ home. Hazy, dark reddish orange appearance with a smallish tan head. Toasty grainy, caramel, grassy, straw aroma. Citrus fruity, toasty caramel malty, grassy, hay flavor. Actually a nice Vienna.

Translucent amber with a minimal tan head.  Toffee, apple blossom, and mild herbal hops in the nose.  Taste is only lightly sweet with just enough hops to cut through and clean things up.  Light body, medium thin texture.  The apple/fruit notes dont fit the lager description, but the mellow, herbal hopping comes across distinctly German to me.  Feels like a Vienna-Bock or amber bock.  Simple, malt forward, and tasty.  Thanks, Matt.
definitely an above average lager, more toffee and buttery notes like a marzen or oktoberfest. clean, somewhat dry finish. i liked it alot.

12oz bottle poured into glass. Dark amber color with a very thin head. Aroma is mostly malty with subtle hints of caramel. Flavor is a little watery but carries with it a nice sweet malt backing. Pretty good.

Nice deep golden orange pour with a thin yellowish head. Aroma is caramel malt and bread. Toasted biscuits. Flavor is a little sweet but also harshly bitter and oddly metallic. Like rusty nails or pennies. Perhaps oxidized?  Hard to drink. Has potential though. I'd like to try this fresh.

Bottle--pours a full copper color with a short lasting head and a slight touch of carbonation.  Muted aromal of caramel and honey.  Taste was full of caramel with biscuit in the middle, followed by a soft finish of hops.  Gets better when warmed slightly.  Variety pack, Publix.
Cloudy amber color with an off-white head.  Aroma of caramel, toasted malt,and hint of hops.  Caramel flavor with hint of honey and toasted malt.  Decenet beer!

Aroma is sweet caramel malt. Appearance is hazy copper with small tan head. Taste is caramel malt forward, honey. A very sweet beer. Palate is medium +. Overall not my favorite. To sweet for a Vienna. Not crisp at all.

Mild sweet aroma with hints of biscuits.  Pours a clear reddish-amber, with a dusting and ring of white head.  Slightly sweet flavor, with a lingering bready note.  Light on the palate, and easy drinking.  Not much going on here, but not a bad beer at all.

Pours a hazy copper color with a large off-white head.  Aroma of caramel malt, light toast, and very light floral hops. Flavor of sweet caramel malts, biscuits, and some very light hoppy bitterness at the finish. Very surprised by this one, quite good.
Pours an orange brown with fizzy white head. Nose is boozy & grainy. Taste is a bit over carbed, dry muted. Not much going on.

Caramel, fruit, and roast aroma.  Amber with white head.  Caramel, roast, and full bodied flavor.  Decent balance with mild bitterness.  

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPhone
12 ounce bottle purchased at Total Wine Pembroke Pines, FL for $1.99 Very good.

Originally reviewed: 3/30/10. Poured into a pint glass. Had with lunch today. Pours a rusty orange with a dense off-white head on top. Great retention; left some spotty lace and sip rings on the glass. Nothing in the nose is very prominent. Some malts, caramel notes, and hints of grass. 

The body is smooth and creamy. Carbonation level is low-to-moderate. Eases consumption for sure. The flavors on this along with the aftertaste really remind me of a Marzen/Ofest. Big malt presence, mild caramel flavoring, light hops, and the finish is very doughy and bready. Light ethanol taste on the backend as well. Again, Lakefront has made another great beer.

Pours a rusty brown color with a small dissipating head. Nose is bark, malt and toffee. Taste is malty, with a dry mildly sweet cigar taste. Finish is dry and short. Average drinkable brew, nothing outstanding, a little short in flavor in my opinion. Quaff Score 5 / 10
Pours a dark amber with a beige head and sweet aroma of malt and caramel. Taste is sweet, of malts, caramel, bread, and fruit flavors with a slight bitter finish. Decent brew.

This is a great everyday beer for me. It has a Sweeter aftertaste that leaves the palate refreshed and wanting more. More of a summer beer as it is not an IPA or a Stout that I usually drink. Living in Milwaukee it I love drinking local beers and this is one of my instant go to beers.
On tap. Pours a nice rich creamy head. Coppery color accents the malty aroma. Sweet taste on the first sip, then a rush of hops. Milwaukees best Vienna style lager.

Appearance was reddish amber with creamy 1 finger white diminishing head,spotty lacing. Aromas was sweet caramel and honey malts. Mild citrusy herbal  and spicey hops. Taste was sweet honey malts upfront with lemony piney hops in the backend. Palate was smooth light carbonation with meduim body with average length sherry-like warming finish. Smooth and Warming...

12oz bottle into a pint glass.

Pours a hazy medium copper with a one finger head that refuses to ago away.

Smells quite floral with some caramel and biscuit.

Taste is all floral up front with caramel following close behind. There is a lot of biscuit about halfway through all fading away to a moderate bitterness. Mouthfeel is fairly full for the style.

Overall this beer surprised me. It is really good with my one complaint being I wish the finish was a little crisper. Besides that a pretty outstanding beer.

This beer has a heavy grain aroma, which may reflect its barley content. My bottle was unstable for reasons unknown, which gave the pour a huge head not usually seen on Vienna lagers. Its a murky copper color and fairly still after the initial explosiveness. Semi-sweet flavor with decent hop balance. Good medium bodied lager, maybe has some mineral content that makes it feel more filling.
Delicious vienna style lager. Round and complex vienna malt character on tap. Bottles are more crisp and possibly a bit drier. I miss drinking this on tap in Riverwest.
Caramel malts and bread in aroma.  The flavor is caramel, bread and very smooth.  Not complicated in flavor, just a very good amber.
Malty sweet but light and smooth. Caramel, nut, toast, leading to a hint of hops at the end. Very full and drinkable.

Bottle pours amber with a white head. Aroma is faint with slight notes of toffee/biscuit. Flavor is malt driven with a touch of earth, but not a whole lot going on to balance out the sweetness. Not a bad beer, but one was definately enough. Overall body is light to moderate.

Pour is fairly clear honey gold with a modest off white head in this glass that retains fairly poorly, to be honest. The nose is caramel, biscuits, and some florals, I suppose. This one is lightly bitter, more biscuits, caramel dominant, florals, modest cream.... This one is fairly nice
Pours a clear amber. Thin white head. Aroma is light but malty. Flavor is nothing special.
Pours a nice amber color with a thick head, had a nice smooth roasty taste. Had on tap at Sobelmans in WI.
Pours a medium tan with very little head.  Smells a bit sour, tastes a bit roasted.  Its an okay beer, but not my style.

Location: 12 oz bottle from Buy Rite, 12/30/11


Aroma: The nose has a fairly rich sweetness with mostly fruit and caramel malt notes

Appearance: It pours a slightly hazy amber-orange color with a thin head and light lace

Flavor: Tastes mid-heavy sweet, similar to the nose with lots of caramel malts and fruity flavors

Palate: The body medium, it is a little bit sticky and a little creamy on the mouth, with a soft carbonation

Overall Impression: 
For me, this one was a little too sweet, and lacked hop balance, but I still found it to be a pretty solid offering.  It had a really solid drinkability to it, and works nicely on the mouth.  The aroma is fairly bold, while a not super complex, and the taste lives up to what youre expecting from the nose.  Overall, this is a solid example of the style, that just lacks a bit on something to balance out the sweetness.

Amber w/ frothy white head.  Sweet malt aroma.  Nice taste - caramel malt is up-front, but balanced with a generous amount of grassy-earthy hops.  Also some roasted malt and floral notes.  Medium body.  Good vienna.

UPDATED: DEC 24, 2011 Bottle from Neal - thanks!  Pours brown amber with an off-white head that  quickly fades out to a foam slick.  Aroma is clean, dry malt, some faded floral hops, and a dominant oat presence with some roast.  Taste is a nice combination of clean, semi-roasted malt with oat and some darker malt in the background followed by a touch of sweetness through the finish.  Clean and easy feel in the mouth.  This is a very well made beer and I like it.

Pint at the Oakcrest in Shorewood. This is a creamy and malty amber lager.  It has a nice white foam and a rich caramel flavor, a surprisingly big taste for a lager, which made it one of my favorites in that styles family.  Its not too bold, but it was slightly sweet and smooth, making it worthy of multiple re-visits.  This is one that is pleasing for the masses, but still not boring at all.

Pours clear reddish orange with nice lacing white head. Aroma of some pine, metallic, caramel and some nutty. Taste is some pine up front, caramel, grain, and biscuit sweet, and a clean slightly bitter finish best offering from this brewery i had

355ml brown bottle. Deep honey gold in colour. Thin and creamy white cap. Nose has caramel malts, grains, sweetish. Flavour has sweet caramel malts, grain background, some bread/light toast. Hint of hop toward the end. Sweet caramel aftertaste. Average in body and carbonation. Hinting at oktoberfest bier here, tasty, accessible, easy drinking.

355ml bottle pours a nice amber color with 1 finger of white head and leaves behind some nice lacing.  Aroma is flowery hops and a hint of caramel.  Taste is predominately a lingering hop bitterness with some underlying malty sweetness.  Slightly better than average amber beer.

12oz bottle. Mildly hazy amber color, minimal off-white head, Some lace. Light body, lighter carbonation. lighter malt aroma, caramel, some tropical fruit. Nice, dark sweet/savory taste. A drinkable brew with a light but pleasant aroma. Not bad.
An all malt masterpiece! Very smooth flavor and dangerously drinkable.. A real mans session beer right here!

On tap at the brewery. A nice drinkability to this. orange body and soapy head, spicy pepper and clove and nutmeg. Above average mouthfeel. Hoppy grapefruit c-hops, good malting with caramel, good amber.Decent balance. Just not the greatest drinker for me, wanted something edgier.

Serving: 12 oz. bottle from State Line Liquors.  It pours a nice deep amber color with a small head of off white foam.  The nose has a good amount of biscuit and toasted malt.  The flavor has a slight hop twinge but leans heavily on those toasted notes with a bit of toasted marshmallow too.  Light to medium body makes for easy drinking and the slightly dry finish leaves you wanting another sip.  Pretty solid stuff.

Bottle (thanks Jason). Pours a amber color with a off white head that fades to a collar. Aroma vegteble and grassy malt with a subtle caramel. Taste is more vegteble and subtle fruit and a malty backbone. Palate is thin and chaulky dry finish. Very drinkable!

A: The beer pours amber in color with a finger of white head.

S: Not too much aroma to this.  Bready malt with a bit of toffee and yeast.  Some toasted malt with a little bit of a butter note toward the back end.  Sort of bland and plain.

T: The flavor is also sort of bland and uninteresting.  Bread and toasted malts with a little bit of a biscuit flavor.  There is some very light hopping and minimal bitterness.  Also some butter to the flavor.

M: Light to medium in body with a medium level of carbonation.

O: Nowhere near as delicious as the Cherry Lager.

Bottle from Marys in OK.  Pours a clear to semi hazy orange color with a small white head. Aroma is major hops and grains. Lots of sweet malts on the nose. Flavor is super nutty and malty. Almost hard to drink. Granted Im drunk and rating with one eye open. There we are America.
Tap. Mostly clear amber pour with a small white head. Aroma is a very mild caramel malt. Taste is terrific - hop profile with mild caramel malt. Nice brew.
Creamy appearance, rich amber color, aromatic nose. Disappointing taste for a lager. Too much hops, not enough malt.

Draught at Red Robin (served way too cold):  Aroma of malt and barley.  Poured copper/amber in color with a large, creamy, dense, off-white head that diminished but lasted throughout.  Clear.  Slightly sparkling.  Flavor is medium sweet and lightly bitter.  Tastes of malt, hops, and barley.  Medium body.  Thin, dry texture.  Average carbonation.  Dry, malt and barley finish.  Very macro-like.

Pours a nice rich brown with a frothy head.  Aroma is of malt and lager yeast.  Bready and Biscuit-like.  Taste is very malty with a nice bite at the end that offsets the sweetness.  Tones of chocolate and biscuit.  Mouthfeel is smooth and rich with a crisp finish.
Pours brown with a small white head and gives off a malty, sour aroma.  Sweet malty, caramel flavor with a sticky sweet finish.
Bottle. Poured red amber with medium foamy head. Pleasant malty and hayey aroma. Light to medium body, some oiliness or rather syrupyness with a sweet finish.
user_location: Munchen an der Willamette, Oregon, USA

text: Lakefront is among the most consistent Wisconsin brewers (Tyranena is up there, too), and Riverwest (honoring a trendy neighborhood near the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee) is one of Lakefronts best. Riverwest is terrifically smooth, full-bodied and sweet with a glorious amber color and thick head. Roll it around the tongue and youll get little hints of bitterness before it again gives way to a finish that has the same smoothness and sweetness as the start.

Pours medium amber with a medium tan head.  Caramel and toast malt, but not overpowering.  Soft carbonation, slick feel with long finish.  Medium sweet, light bitterness.  This is a very drinkable beer with nice malt flavor.

12 ounce bottle - $1.69 at Olde Crabapple Bottle Shoppe in Alpharetta, Georgia.

Appearance: Pours a clear, amber-brown body with a white head topping one inch.

Smell: Mildly bready, yeasty-toned aroma with a toasted accent to it and supporting notes of fruit and powdered spices.

Taste: Lightly toasty, lightly nutty malts with a mild touch of sugared sweetness. Spicy, yeasty, estery, and with a small bit of dried citrus midway, all pretty fleeting. Faintly bitter. Drying finish, with a slackening, thinning body.

Mouthfeel: Medium-light body. Medium-light carbonation.

Overall: Though it lacks the real depth of character and malt complexities of the finer examples, its still suitable as a mild, easy-drinking lager.
One of Belching Gals favorite regular beers. Nice citrus/ ginger aroma. Balanced sweet malts with spicey hoppy finish. Yummy. 8 Burps.

This pours a super dark orange, easy to miss the orange and mistake for brown. Lightly clear despite the darkness, tope head that rises abouta finger but falls quickly. Very light and watery lacing...Dead aroma, not much going on here at all. Light skunk you get from a macro lager with a hint of malted rye...The taste is a little better, still light with a lack of flavor but its not skunky has something to it. Light amber taste, rye and caramel, a little hoppy finish with a touch of skunk finally...Super light feel, kinda tough to drink the whole thing.

This is something new to my tastebuds, but nothing special. Decent taste but thats it, worth skipping.

Pours a reddish copper with a thick frothy light tan head. Nose is malt and sugar. Fairly creamy and well carbonated, the front taste profile is all malt while a hops note lingers on the finish. A well balanced beer but it doesnt seperate itself from the pack. Tastes great with split pea soup and matzo crackers.

Bottle from Breeze Thru.  Pours an orangey-tan with fine bubbles.  Aroma is sweet caramel malt, some bread, some sugar.  Taste is thin syrup, caramel, some fruitiness.  Finishes thin.  I have had this a number of times, and thought it was slightly superior to this one.
An Amber lager with a touch more character than most, but it is still an Amber lager how are you supposed to get excited.

Bottle. Pours copper orange with an off white head. Sweet malty aroma with some bready notes and faint hops. The flavor has sweet and toasty malts, some bready notes, and some light hops in the finish. Decent.

On tap.  An excellent lager.  Pours a lovely dark copper color with about a finger of foam.  Taste is of caramel malts followed by a pleasant hop finish.  Definitely one of the better lagers Ive had.
bottle, blind sample, GLBN tasting. decent beer, was told it was a stein beer, toasted malts, berry like sweetness, caramel malts, nutty notes, drinkable, a tad sweet. ok
A hazy, amber-brown pour with off-white head.  It has a faint caramel aroma.  The body is smooth and light with average carbonation.  The taste is moderately sweet and it has a mostly clean finish.

bottle consumed 7/12/10.

dark dirty pale copper color with a white head.

it smells and tastes like yeast, orange meat, lemon peel and toasty malt. the flavor finishes with a light dryness.

this reminds me a lot of yuengling?... only better. 6/3/6/4/14/3.3

aroma is clean, lightly grassy.  low caramel at this point, no hints of toast to come.  appearance is well polished translucent burnished amber with active carb and messy ring that lingers.  flavor is nice toast, soft caramel devoid of cloying notes, lightly prickly hop character in background late and hints of spiciness.
12oz bottle. Murky bronze, good persistent head. Aroma light toasted malt but a little sour. Fairly standard amber with vienna notes. Malt dominated  but a style I struggle with
Bottle. Clear copper with white head. Aromas of caramel, biscuit, nuts. Flavors of caramel, biscuit, nuts, citrus. Balanced finish. Medium-thin body with round mouthfeel and moderate carbonation.

Sampled at Binnys of Glen Ellyn, IL. during an Oktoberfest tasting. Poured from a 12oz bottle to a sampler glass with a lightly hazed, brownish amber hue, modest, off white, bubbly head foam, and light spots and streaks of lacing. The nose was lightly toasted malt and a touch of caramel sweetness. The flavor was similar, with some low hop bitterness, and a little dryness to the finish. A nice, flavorful Vienna, especially suited for the fall.
UPDATED: JUN 7, 2015 Originally had at the brewery tour. Very nice reddish Vienna lager. Easy drinking but flavorful. Serving: Bottle and tap

Pours clear reddish orange with nice lacing white head. Aroma of some pine, metallic, caramel and some nutty. Taste is some pine up front, caramel, grain, and biscuit sweet, and a clean slightly bitter finish. Not bad.

Pours a deep amber color with a very creamy, off-white head. Aroma has a great floral and citrus nose with a touch of toasted malt late. Flavor has an early citrus orange taste but this is quickly taken over by a smooth toasted malt and finishes with a sweet caramel malt ending. Body is light with a crisp feel. A pretty good brew overall. I typically dont care for amber or vinna styled brews but this one was really well made. The hops was the perfect amount to compliment the malt rich flavors.
Had this beer while waiting for the Jackson Browne/David Lindley show at Riverside last night. Was enjoyable, but I quickly opted for Stevens Point "2012" next.

[Bottle] Pours a light brown color with a small amount of off-white head. Aroma of toasted nut, caramel and light grains. The taste was of caramel malts, molasses, light biscuit and crisp hopping. Average carbonation and mouthfeel. A pretty solid beer.
Pours a golden amber, white head, hoppy flavor, smooth mouth feel, hop bitters on the finish, not bad though, mild carbonation.

Complex aroma that starts with all malt but the caramel tones can be picked up as well.  Nice deep orange / amber color, light head, medium carbonation, medium body.  Very drinkable.  Nice finish.  Good all around.

12 oz. Clear amber with a lasting head. Nose of caramel, apple and dry grass. Flavor is a nice blend of the same, with some toasted pecan as well. Light-medium body is well balanced, lightly tingly, and highly sessionable.

rerate.  caramel orange/red colored body.  nose is highly fruity (esters are high) for the style and slightly phenolic as well.  rich, creamy, mildly sweet, medium chewiness in the finish.  could benefit from more dryness as it would reduce the chewy/full/rounded feeling in the finish, but overall its mild and tends to the sweet side (low hop flavor and bitterness) with basic munich/two-row/car-pils.  if I had to guess Id say american-made german bock style, the fruity esters and phenols being out of place in proper german-made lager.  my notes from 2003 seem to be more positive but thats too long ago to have any faith in understanding where my palate was at.

Bottle from Friar Tuck in Savoy, IL. Pours a medium to dark amber with an pale beige head. Aroma of munich malts and dark bread grains. Lighter side of medium bodied with average carbonation, smooth mouthfeel. Flavor of bready german malts countered by a very light herbal hoppiness. Finish had some off flavors- which could be because its old. I could not tell if it was astringency or isovaleric acid.

Poured from 12oz bottle, pours an amber color with nice white fizzy head, aroma is very malty and has a nice touch of hops to it, flavor is roasty with a kick of hops to it, one of the better Lakefront brews Ive had.

In my opinion the best of the Lakefront brews Ive tried to date.  The tapper poured a nice dark amber with a good head.  Aroma of mainly malt and hops.  A smooth malt taste with a decent hop ending that was nice.  Overall, this brew satisfied nicely.  I will likely pick up a sixer at a future oppertunity.
user_location: Town of Maple Creek, Wisconsin, USA

text: Hazy dark amber body with a firm two inch off white head with good persistence.  A toasty-bready malt aroma, slight brown sugar sweetness, and almost imperceptible phenolic sting.  Medium bodied mouthfeel with good, lively carbonation.  The flavor is heavy on the toasty malts, with a firm melanoidin sweetness.  Low hop flavor, but moderate hop bitterness that catches at the start and lingers, with the sweetness, past the finish.  Definitely a good beer, with a strong melanoidin character that is fairly unique.

(bottle) Lightly hazy amber beer with a big off-white head. Rich toasted malt aroma, caramel, bread, and light hops.  Flavor is caramel, sweet and lots of fruit (berries); bright, slight tartness. Mild, underlying bitterness that comes out in the finish. Medium bodied.

Poured a clear honey color with a thin white head.  Sweet, grain, malty aroma.  Taste is malty and slightly nutty.  Hints of fruit as well.  Finish is very smooth and crisp with some caramel notes.  Very well balanced.
With a light amber color, this amber beer leans a little more towards the pale ale side of the spectrum with a fair amount of hops, but still has some malt characteristics to it.
From a 12 oz bottle,Weird smell to it ,looks amber and cloudy,thick head,carmel.A different take on a amber lager

(Bottle, Monks Café Wallingatan, Stockholm) Amber colour with huge, off-white head leaving traces of lacing. Malty, clean nose with notes of bread and caramel. Malty taste with bread, wort, hints of caramel and a touch of orange peel and dried fruit. Medium body with soft mouthfeel. Medium spicy bitterness. Balanced sweetness. Not too exciting, but a well balanced and tasty vienna.

Bottle from Whole Foods Bowery.  Sweet cocoa, cereal, honey and caramel.  Both medium light and chewy.  Pour has a great look... dark copper, tint of orange and brown, with frothy off white head.   Finishes tangy and bitter.  Excellent for the style!  3.55

Pours amber, with a thin ring of foam. Subtle aromas of caramel and some fruity notes. Drier than I expected. Clean and crisp. Not particularly unique, but no evident flaws. Thanks to lithy for this one!

Very clear pale brown, short persistent creamy head. Strange interplay of aromas tropical fruit, mushy apricot, fresh manure, mothballs, Jello, campfire. Equally odd flavor features peach and cherry, barnyard/sweaty horse, leather, wet wool, rancid butter. Mouthfeel is slippery and buttery. Cranberry and maraschino cherry finish, menthol and sheepsmilk cheese aftertaste. Theres no f**king way in hell this isnt a brettanomyces fermented beer. Which is why Im kinda digging it. As an Vienna/amber lager, its just wrong all over.

Bottle (nearly was a slow gusher). Pours with a hazy brownish golden body. Fading off-white head. Aroma of caramel, toast and bread. Light fruit notes. Flavor of fruits, toast, cardboard, diacetyl. Slight rotten fruit as well. A touch of toffee. Very carbonated mouthfeel.

Pours a cloudy amber color with a medium head. Aroma is not particularly good some vegetal notes, some burnt plastic, some good fruitiness and hoppy characteristics show through as well making it less insufferable. Flavor is not too bad, fruity and malty with a little card board. 
Kind of sucks because I really really wanted to like this one.

Lakefront Brewery, Inc.--Riverwest Stein Beer--All Malt Amber Lager--2007 Release--12 oz. Bottle--5.70% ABV--20 IBUs.  (4.1 / 5.0)  Amber Lager--Stone.  Beer of the Month Club Selection March 2007.  Tight settled aged sediment.  Thin laced off white head.  Clear bright rich amber color.  Mild hop floral malt front.  Creamy smooth rich malty mild sweet caramel malt amber lager body.  Clean smooth mild hop end Smooth well made aged well Amber Lager.  Sampled 2/6/2010.

Hazy amber color. Very berryish and appley aroma. Toffeish, worty, berryish and appley flavor with hints of glue. Unpleasantly appley and solventy.

Bottled (bottled 04/2009)@MC
Clear ruby color, medium-sized off-white head. Some wet wood, maybe a bit smokey, hard water-metal. Active carbonation. Wet wood and caramel in the flavor.

had a few of these while camping in the rain with some friends in WI.  not the best note-taking environment, but i managed to write

"fair amber ale with interesting background flavor = 2.5"

i see now that it was unmalted barley hiding out back there, and yes, i was dissapointed that it was not "hot rocks" steinbier.  that would have made the whole camping in the rain thing much more tolerable.

anyway, i had bought all the New Glarus beers i could find on my way up there and was anxious to move on to those. can you blame me?

Draft at Lakefront.  Pine and CO2 in the aroma, also lots of malt some of which is toasty.  Flavor begins and ends quickly.  The hops bitterness is subtle and likes the sides of the tongue.  Very pleasant to drink, my Bud Light buddy enjoyed drinking it all night.  This speaks to a lot of Lakefronts beers, they dont have tremendous depth of flavor but theyre quaffable and tasty.  Yay beer!
Dark brown-orange, thin off white cover.  Toast aroma, caramelized sugar, burnt candy, cocoa.  Taste is more burnt sugar, cocoa.

True to form I drank this from a stein my son bought me.

Pours a dark amber with a creamy off-white head. Nose is not impressive. Has a thick consistency on the tongue. Toasted nuts quickly pleasure the palate.Little malt, only a brief glimpse of hops. This brew probably would suck if it were not for the nuttiness of it. Very nice. I can feel it from my tastebuds to my inner nostrils.
Pours amber small white head.Aroma very lite at best,what it lacks in aroma it makes up with a nice full body flavor.Flavors of caramel and malts.
Fairly closed aroma, subtle toasted nuttiness.  Flavor is very nice, perfectly balanced with a rich malty flavor.  I wish I had enough of this to fill my liter stein with!

Pours amber with a mostly receding off-white head. Notes of sour mash, caramel, lightly grapefruit, nuts, and coarse hops. Medium bodied with moderate carbonation. A bit tangy, the malt may have been overwhelmed by hops, or there may have been a slight infection.

UPDATED: JAN 6, 2012 I had this at some classy bar that was practically empty in Milwaukee and this was not a good beer.  The bar couldve had issues with keeping their beer cold for a good amount of time or something, because I thoroughly enjoy this brewery but this beer was just horrible.  It tasted like pure malt syrup, not good at all and maybe Ill try again and re-rate.....Re-rated after having a bottle at my to be father-in-laws for a holiday meal.  This was much much much better than when I first tried.  Good maltiness, bumping up my rating by almost a full point.

12 oz single from Archers. Deep orange hazy body. Medium sized frothy beige head. Mild roasty aromas with caramel malt and apples. Sweet malty taste is combined with apples, and slight roasty almost smoked hints. Bread crust too. Good bite in the finish.
nice flavor and mild-sweet malts.  Pours light brown-orange with a shory head.  Very smooth.
